{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655780"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18678"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18678"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78540"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10328"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26914"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78540","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78540"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe skull is a rigid container housing the brain, blood vessels, and cerebrospinal fluid. Understanding the normal intracranial pressure is crucial for managing neurological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately describes the normal intracranial pressure in a healthy adult at rest?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["0-5 mmHg","7-15 mmHg","20-25 mmHg","30-40 mmHg","45-50 mmHg"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe normal \u003Cstrong\u003E7-15 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E intracranial pressure range reflects the balanced relationship between brain tissue, cerebrospinal fluid (CSF), and blood volume within the rigid skull, as described by the Monroe-Kellie doctrine.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E20-25 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents mildly elevated intracranial pressure that may cause symptoms\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E0-5 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This is below normal and would indicate pathologically low pressure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E30-40 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This represents significantly elevated pressure requiring urgent intervention\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E45-50 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This is severely elevated pressure that can be life-threatening\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMaintaining normal intracranial pressure is essential for adequate cerebral perfusion. When one component increases (e.g. brain swelling), there must be compensatory decreases in other components (e.g. CSF or blood volume) to maintain normal pressure within the fixed cranial vault.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intracranial pressure normally ranges between 7-15 mmHg in adults at rest.","The Monroe-Kellie doctrine states that the sum of brain tissue, cerebrospinal fluid, and blood volume must remain constant within the rigid skull.","Changes in one intracranial component must be offset by reciprocal changes in others to maintain normal pressure."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T12:36:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T12:37:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78540"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id"